{
  "text": "Similar to the small subunit processome, the nucleolar pre-60S particle, which is compositionally related to Nsa1-containing particles [CITATION_1] , accumulates upon starvation. We analysed purified nucleolar pre-60S particles by cryo-EM, revealing a high-resolution core (3.4 Å) that was further sub-classified into three states, which we structurally resolved at resolutions of 4.3 Å (state 1), 3.7 Å (state 2) and 4.6 Å (state 3) ( Table 1,  Extended Data Figs 2, 3) . These three states, together with cross-linking and mass spectrometry data, resulted in the identification of 21 ribosome assembly factors (Extended Data Table 1 and Supplementary Dataset 1). Atomic models could be completed for 18 of these proteins, and homology and poly-alanine models were used for proteins such as Ebp2, Mak11 and Ytm1, which were located in more flexible regions (Fig. 1, Extended Data Fig. 4) .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "7271012"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "7271012": {
      "title": "Composition and functional characterization of yeast 66S ribosome assembly intermediates",
      "abstract": "The pathway and complete collection of factors that orchestrate ribosome assembly are not clear. To address these problems, we affinity purified yeast preribosomal particles containing the nucleolar protein Nop7p and developed means to separate their components. Nop7p is associated primarily with 66S preribosomes containing either 27SB or 25.5S plus 7S pre-rRNAs. Copurifying proteins identified by mass spectrometry include ribosomal proteins, nonribosomal proteins previously implicated in 60S ribosome biogenesis, and proteins not known to be involved in ribosome production. Analysis of strains mutant for eight of these proteins not previously implicated in ribosome biogenesis showed that they do participate in this pathway. These results demonstrate that proteomic approaches in concert with genetic tools provide powerful means to purify and characterize ribosome assembly intermediates."
    }
  }
}